    <statement><div><p>A Grade 10 mathematics teacher has a magical number sorter that only accepts <alert>rational numbers</alert>.</p>
<p>From the list below, <alert>EXACTLY THREE</alert> of the numbers are rational. Which ones are they?</p>
<p/>
<p/>
<p/><ol marker="(1)">
<li><m>\frac{3}{10}</m></li>
<li><m>\sqrt{2}</m></li>
<li><m>\frac{12}{5}</m></li>
<li><m>\sqrt{10}</m></li>
<li><m>\sqrt{3}</m></li>
<li><m>-9</m></li>
</ol>  </div></statement>
    <solution><div><h3>Worked Solution</h3>
<p>A rational number is any number that can be expressed as a fraction <m> \frac{p}{q} </m> where <m> p </m> and <m> q </m> are integers and <m> q \neq 0 </m>.</p>
<p>The decimal representation of a rational number either terminates (stops at some point) or repeats (continues but has a repeating pattern).</p>
<p>The square root of a perfect square is a rational number.</p>
<p>Therefore, from the given numbers, the list of rational numbers are: (<m>{\frac{3}{10}}</m>,<m>{-9}</m>,<m>{\frac{12}{5}}</m>)</p></div></solution>
    <answer><p><m>(1), (3), (6)</m></p></answer>
